# Event Projection Skill

## Purpose
Guide an AI agent through building read-side projections from event streams in CQRS.

## Sections to Generate

### When to Use This Skill
Creating a new query view, optimizing an existing query that hits the write model, or migrating from a shared read/write schema to separated read models.

### Projection Concept
A projection subscribes to one or more event streams and maintains a **read model** optimized for a specific query pattern. Each projection owns its data — there is no shared schema between projections.

### Projection Responsibilities
1. Consume events from the bus (or replay them from the event store)
2. Apply the events to update its read model
3. Track the last event consumed (checkpoint) for resumability
4. Be idempotent: re-consuming an event must not change the read model further

### Read Model Design
- Tailored to the query, not normalized — denormalize freely
- Pre-compute aggregations and counts that the query needs
- Indexed for the query patterns expected
- Owned by the projection — never shared with other projections or with the write model

### Resumability
- Persist checkpoint (e.g. last event ID consumed) atomically with the read model update
- On restart, replay from the checkpoint forward
- For new projections: replay from the beginning of the stream (no shortcuts)

### Eventual Consistency
- Read models lag the write model — accept this
- UX strategies: optimistic UI, polling, push notifications, "your change has been saved" feedback while consistency catches up

### Anti-patterns to Avoid
- Projections that query other projections (build a third one if needed)
- Projections that issue commands (only sagas/process managers do this)
- Sharing read models across projections (each is independent)
- Storing the entire history in a projection (it's a derived view, not the source)

### Verification
A correct projection: starting from an empty read model and replaying all events produces the current state; consuming an event twice produces no further change; can be rebuilt at any time by truncating the read model and replaying from the beginning.
